mjfsH2YyeLlquKlgn77%2B8fkP%2BtyuyPjWbN4mU5MaL8px4oP3sZiurnf%2BJnP96vX7zex06MYRM3RNyx9mMJQJsDA%2FFFR%2B5oEEs6Iq%2FTbZ%2B%2FZfFsOfcw%3D%3D" id="w1_2_3_4_7_8"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#e9b0a0;strokeColor=#b8402a;fontColor=#511810;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="1289" y="1101" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Meat-eater problem&lt;br&gt;(saved humans eat animals)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+4+7+8+9]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   66k lives-eq/$1k · 70% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 30%&lt;br&gt;(Michael Dickens, Vasco Grilo)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + nature_intrinsic_value + climate_tipping_points + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + meat_eater_problem&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The meat-eater problem: a dollar of human global health also buys decades of that person&#x27;s meat consumption, and factory farming it causes suffering the animal circle now counts. Each present-human org is charged an additive penalty — farmed-animal life-years caused per human DALY, times the suffering per factory-farmed life-year, times the animal&#x27;s welfare range. Under a heavy animal welfare range the penalty can exceed the human benefit, so saving human lives looks net-harmful. Only bites once animals count, so it requires animals_somewhat; and it is a near-term human-vs-animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans), where x-risk dominates and the meat bookkeeping is moot. || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 nature_intrinsic_value → 4 climate_tipping_points → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 9 meat_eater_problem" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJytWWtv2zgW%2FSsXwc6unbEdWX6nmwXSPKZFkzZIMxsMmsKlJdrmRBK1pBTX7XR%2B%2Bx5Ski0nysQL74cGqkSee%2B77kv6%2B5%2FMpS4PkRPp873Dv4ICOjo7oRjERUSLJU%2Bzb