c%2F21tSk2JW0Y4am8lYrVUv83CxxfXJyfnZZq6OPJEiFWWSIfrbOxWFG5MW1MuGky1%2Fm4dc01Z8qflRL46QD4jNAnC9dSP5uxq5g6jugCwC1zraw0r9n%2FmEnk9bKWTSEN%2Bv7H1z%2Foa6sk40e9fhePTWocFePLJ%2BdzPs3dVP4GdPPm7cf1rHaYjT9myBsXPwRhCBRgYX6YKP2sBAlmRVn6Xbz347%2Bm4sXe" id="w1_2_3_4_7_8_9_18"><mxCell style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fontSize=11;fillColor=#c9b3dd;strokeColor=#4a2a78;fontColor=#201040;" vertex="1" parent="1"><mxGeometry x="2172" y="2124" width="395" height="140" as="geometry"/></mxCell></object><object label="Net-negative lives&lt;br&gt;(animal suffering dominates)&lt;br&gt;[1+2+3+4+7+8+10]&lt;br&gt;→ Shrimp Welfare Project&lt;br&gt;   198k lives-eq/$1k · 60% best&lt;br&gt;   runner-up Wild insects (humane pesticides) · 40%&lt;br&gt;(Brian Tomasik, David Benatar)" tooltip="&lt;b&gt;parochial + far_away_humans + animals_somewhat + nature_intrinsic_value + climate_tipping_points + animals_matter_a_lot + suffering_focused + net_negative_animal_lives&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;The net-negative-lives hypothesis: factory-farmed and wild animals endure more suffering than wellbeing, so their lives are not worth living. Reducing that suffering is worth more per dollar (you are mitigating a catastrophe, not improving a good life), most of all for the astronomical wild-invertebrate populations. Combined with the meat-eater problem it drives human charities firmly net-negative — every human sustained means more net-negative farmed lives. Presupposes counting wild/invertebrate animals, so it requires animals_matter_a_lot; and like the meat-eater problem it is a near-term animal get-off point, not combined with astronomical-stakes longtermism (no_discounting_future_humans). || Chain: 0 parochial → 1 far_away_humans → 2 animals_somewhat → 3 nature_intrinsic_value → 4 climate_tipping_points → 7 animals_matter_a_lot → 8 suffering_focused → 10 net_negative_animal_lives" link="https://www.squiggle-language.com/playground#code=eJylWWtz27gV%2FSt3PN1WSi2ZpN5O0xnHj00mduJxvPXsxBkFIiEJNUmwAGVFyWZ